"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the Academy of Medical Sciences (WSC028)&#xa0;\nSummary\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\nIntroduction\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhy do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder? \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Attrition\n in academic medicine\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and\n PhD students in academic career\ns? Are there examples of good practice?\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\nBetter \ninforming\n medical students\n about academic careers\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPromoting institutional cultural change\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMentoring\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nFlexible Fellowships\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat role shoul\nd the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?\n&#xa0;\n              \nThe Academy of Medical Sciences \n&#xa0;\nThe Academy of Medical Sciences promotes advances in medical science and campaigns to ensure these are converted into healthcare benefits for society. Our Fellows are the UK’s leading medica\nl scientists from hospitals and general practice, academia, industry and the public service. \n&#xa0;\nThe Academy seeks to play a pivotal role in determining the future of medical science in the UK, and the benefits that society will enjoy in years to come. We ch\nampion the UK’s strengths in medical science, promote careers and capacity building, encourage the implementation of new ideas and solutions – often through novel partnerships – and help to remove barriers to progress. \n&#xa0;\nAugust 2013\n&#xa0;\n Medical Schools Council, 2013. \nA Survey of Staffing Levels of\n \nMedical Clinical Academics in UK\n \nMedical Schools as at 31 July 201\n2.\n \nhttp://www.medschools.ac.uk/News/Pages/2012_Clinical_Academic_Staff_Survey_published.aspx\n.\n \nIbid\n.\n UKRC, 2009. \nFemale Attrition, Retention and Barriers to Careers in SET \nAcademic Research\n. Royal Society of Edinburgh, 2012. Tapping all our talents. NAS, 2010. \nGender Differences at Critical Transitions in the Careers of\n \nScience, Engineering, and Mathematics Faculty\n.\n \nRCUK Annual \nR\neport (2009)\n: Sustainability of the UK \nResearch Workforce\nhttp://www.rcuk.ac.uk/documents/researchcareers/SustainabilityoftheUKResearchWorkforce.pdf\n The Academy of Medical Sciences\n \n(2013\n)\n:\n \nThe Representation of Women within the Academy’s Fellowship \nhttp://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/index.php?pid=291\n Medical Schools Council 2007. Women in Clinical Academia: Attracting and Developing the\n Medical and Dental Workforce of the Future.\n Athena SWAN: Measuring Success 2011\nhttp://www.athenaswan.org.uk/sites/default/files/Athena%20SWAN%20Imp\nact%20Report%202011.pdf\n Equality Challenge Unit, 2010. \nMentoring:\n \nprogressing women’s careers in higher education\n. \n \nBalmer, D. \net al\n., 2011.\n \nHow Mentoring Relationships Evolve: A Longitudinal Study of Academic Pediatricians in a Physician Educator \nFaculty Development Program: Journal of Continuing Education in the Health Professions, v. 31, p. 81-86.\n"